{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "1. Architecture & Data Flow",
  "description": "Full pipeline walkthrough, in call order: mic -> VAD -> STT -> safeword -> orchestrator -> backend adapter -> TTS -> playback. Each step calls out the data handoff (shape/dtype crossing the boundary) and any performance-relevant design decision at that point.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "title": "Start here",
      "description": "**ConvoBox pipeline, top to bottom.**\n\n```\n   mic  ->  VAD  ->  local STT  ->  safeword check  ->  orchestrator  ->  backend adapter\n                                        |                                    |\n                                   (deterministic,                    OpenCode /\n                                    no LLM)                           Claude Code / ...\n                                                                            |\n                                                                    local streaming TTS\n```\n\nThis tour follows one utterance through every stage in the order it actually happens at runtime, not file/directory order. Watch the **data handoff** called out at each step — the shape/dtype changes as audio becomes numbers becomes text becomes routing decisions becomes speech again.\n\nSee `README.md` → Architecture for the original design diagram this pipeline implements.\n\nEach step below is anchored by both a line number and a text pattern — if the code has moved since this tour was written, CodeTour re-locates the step by searching for the pattern rather than trusting a stale line number."
    },
    {
      "file": "scripts/spike.py",
      "line": 38,
      "pattern": "with MicrophoneStream\\(sample_rate=config\\.audio\\.sample_rate",
      "description": "**The whole chain in one line.** This is the actual measurement spike — mic → VAD → STT → logged transcript — with no backend/TTS wiring, useful as an orientation map before diving into each stage:\n\n```python\nwith MicrophoneStream(...) as mic:\n    async for utterance in segmenter.segment(mic.stream()):\n        result = transcriber.transcribe(utterance)\n```\n\n`mic.stream()` is an async generator of raw chunks → `segmenter.segment()` re-yields only complete utterances → `transcriber.transcribe()` turns one utterance into text. Every step below zooms into one of these three calls."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/audio/capture.py",
      "line": 21,
      "pattern": "class MicrophoneStream:",
      "description": "**Stage 1: audio capture.** `MicrophoneStream` wraps a single `sounddevice.InputStream` — continuous streaming, not record-then-stop, because segmentation into utterances is VAD's job downstream, not a fixed capture window.\n\nDeliberately **not** shelling out to platform tools (sox/arecord/powershell) — see README's \"Lessons from an earlier attempt\" for why that was a real command-injection bug in an earlier related project."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/audio/capture.py",
      "line": 42,
      "pattern": "def _callback\\(",
      "description": "**The real-time boundary.** `_callback` runs on PortAudio's own audio thread, not the asyncio event loop — it must be fast and non-blocking. It just copies the incoming buffer and pushes it onto a plain `queue.Queue`.\n\n**Data handoff:** raw device audio → `float32` numpy array, shape `(blocksize,)`, values in `[-1, 1]`. float32 (not int16) because both Silero VAD and faster-whisper consume float32 directly — int16 would force a conversion on every single chunk (see the module-level comment at the top of this file)."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/audio/capture.py",
      "line": 70,
      "pattern": "async def stream\\(self\\) -> AsyncIterator",
      "description": "**Bridging the sync callback thread to async consumers.** `stream()` is an async generator that pulls off the queue via `asyncio.to_thread(self._queue.get)` — blocking the queue-get in a worker thread so it never stalls the event loop.\n\nThe `_CLOSE_SENTINEL` pattern (defined near the top of this file) is what lets `close()` wake up a consumer parked in a blocking `get()` — this exact bridge pattern gets reused later for TTS streaming too (see step on `piper.py`)."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/vad/segmenter.py",
      "line": 23,
      "pattern": "class UtteranceSegmenter:",
      "description": "**Stage 2: voice activity detection.** `UtteranceSegmenter` turns a stream of float32 chunks into discrete utterances using Silero VAD.\n\nTwo deliberate design choices worth noting up front (both in the docstring): a speech run only ends after `min_silence_ms` of *confirmed* silence (tolerant of pauses/disfluencies), and emitted utterances **include** that trailing silence on purpose — it helps STT avoid clipping the last phoneme."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/vad/segmenter.py",
      "line": 51,
      "pattern": "def feed\\(self, chunk: np\\.ndarray\\)",
      "description": "**Data handoff: arbitrary-length chunks → fixed 512-sample windows.** Silero's ONNX model only accepts exactly 512 samples (32ms) at 16kHz. Incoming capture chunks can be any length (and in `feed()`'s own tests, deliberately unaligned to 512 to prove no samples are dropped/duplicated), so they're buffered in `self._carry` and consumed in exact windows here.\n\nReturns a **list** of utterances (not zero-or-one) because a single large chunk can span the end of one utterance and the start of another."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/vad/segmenter.py",
      "line": 87,
      "pattern": "def _process_window\\(self, window: np\\.ndarray\\)",
      "description": "**The core state machine — and where a real hang bug lived.** Every window gets a `prob` from the model (this call happens unconditionally, every ~32ms, even during silence — see the Performance tour for why that's not actually wasted work).\n\nA few lines down, `_EXIT_HYSTERESIS` creates three zones: confidently speech, confidently silent, and an **ambiguous band** in between. The `elif is_speech:` branch just below (not a plain `else:`) is the fix for a bug where ambiguous-band frames were treated as speech and reset the silence timer on every frame — a speaker trailing off gradually could keep an utterance open forever. See the code comment right below it for the full story, and the Review Findings tour for the verification trail."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/vad/segmenter.py",
      "line": 131,
      "pattern": "async def segment\\(",
      "description": "**Data handoff: windows → one concatenated utterance array.** `segment()` is the async-generator wrapper `spike.py` actually calls — consumes chunks, yields complete utterances via `feed()`, and on stream close calls `flush()` to emit anything still in progress.\n\nOutput: a single float32 numpy array (all the 512-sample windows for that utterance concatenated together) — this is exactly what `LocalTranscriber.transcribe()` expects next."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/stt/transcriber.py",
      "line": 24,
      "pattern": "class LocalTranscriber:",
      "description": "**Stage 3: local speech-to-text.** `LocalTranscriber` loads the faster-whisper `WhisperModel` **once**, at construction — model loading is expensive, so this class is meant to be built once and reused across every utterance for the life of the process."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/stt/transcriber.py",
      "line": 33,
      "pattern": "def transcribe\\(self, audio: np\\.ndarray\\)",
      "description": "**Data handoff: utterance array → `TranscriptResult`.** Input is the float32 mono 16kHz array from the segmenter (defensively re-contiguous'd a couple lines down, since faster-whisper needs a contiguous buffer).\n\nOutput bundles the transcript text **with timing as a first-class field** (`latency_ms`, `duration_s`) — not just logged internally — because this project's whole first milestone was proving real accuracy/latency numbers before committing to backend/adapter design. Real measured numbers on this hardware: **STT ~140–200ms, RTF 0.05–0.13** (8–20x faster than real-time)."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/safeword/detector.py",
      "line": 5,
      "pattern": "deliberately a plain normalized-substring match",
      "description": "**Stage 4: the safeword check — deliberately dumb.** This comment says it outright: a plain normalized-substring match, **no ML, no fuzzy matching, no LLM**, on purpose. A hard stop is a safety-critical abort; a human reading this file must be able to predict exactly when it fires. That auditability guarantee is worth more here than the recall a fuzzy matcher would buy.\n\nThis runs on every transcript, in the orchestrator, **before** any busy/idle routing decision — see the next step."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/orchestrator/orchestrator.py",
      "line": 40,
      "pattern": "async def handle_transcript\\(self, transcript: str\\)",
      "description": "**Stage 5: the routing decision.** `handle_transcript` is where a finalized transcript becomes one of three concrete actions:\n\n1. **Hard stop** — checked first, unconditionally, and wins over everything else. It also stops any in-progress TTS/playback — if the user says stop, ConvoBox shouldn't keep talking.\n2. **Interject** — backend is busy, this is a side-comment, not a fresh task.\n3. **Fresh command** — backend is idle.\n\nThe `start_event_loop()` call near the top of this method is itself a fix: see the Review Findings tour for why `is_busy()` needs that loop running to stay accurate."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/adapters/base.py",
      "line": 32,
      "pattern": "class BackendAdapter\\(ABC\\):",
      "description": "**The backend adapter contract.** Three implementations exist and are each verified against a live instance: `OpenCodeAdapter` (HTTP+SSE), `ClaudeCodeAdapter` (bidirectional stream-json subprocess, `src/convobox/adapters/claude_code.py`), `CodexAdapter` (app-server JSON-RPC over stdio, `src/convobox/adapters/codex.py`). The docstring draws a hard line: `send_interject` must never derail a running task, `send_hard_stop` must abort it — these are never allowed to collapse into one \"interrupt\" action.\n\nA paragraph further down is an honesty clause added after review: a hard stop's real-world guarantee is bounded by what the backend actually exposes (see the next step for the concrete case)."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/adapters/opencode.py",
      "line": 82,
      "pattern": "async def events\\(self\\) -> AsyncGenerator",
      "description": "**The OpenCode backend adapter: HTTP + SSE.** `events()` opens a streaming GET and yields typed `BackendEvent`s parsed from each SSE frame in real time — not buffered until the connection closes.\n\n**Data handoff:** raw SSE `data:` frames (JSON text) → typed `BackendEvent` objects (`text | tool_call | tool_result | error | done`). The `finally` block a few lines down clears `self._busy = False` on **any** exit from this generator, not just an observed DONE — a dropped connection or exception used to leave `is_busy()` stuck `True` forever. See Review Findings for the full story."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/orchestrator/orchestrator.py",
      "line": 86,
      "pattern": "def _on_event\\(self, event: BackendEvent\\)",
      "description": "**Backend response → speech.** `_on_event` is where a `TEXT` event from the backend gets turned into spoken audio: strip code blocks (`strip_code_for_speech`, defined at the top of this file) so raw diffs aren't read aloud, then fire synthesis as a **background task**, not awaited inline.\n\nWhy fire-and-forget: synthesis can take noticeably longer than draining the *next* backend event (e.g. a DONE right behind this TEXT), and keeping `is_busy()` fresh matters more than serializing speech with event consumption. `AudioPlayer.play()` (next stage) is itself non-blocking, so this task's only real work is the `synthesize()` await."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/tts/base.py",
      "line": 14,
      "pattern": "def sanitize_text\\(text: str\\)",
      "description": "**The security boundary before any synthesis happens.** `sanitize_text` strips control characters and caps length on text that originates from **untrusted LLM output**. Every concrete `TTSEngine` must call this before synthesizing — this exists directly because of a real command-injection bug in an earlier related project (`voice-opencode`), where response text was interpolated straight into a shell command. See README → \"Lessons from an earlier attempt.\""
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/tts/base.py",
      "line": 42,
      "pattern": "def synthesize_stream\\(self, text: str\\) -> AsyncIterator",
      "description": "**Streaming is the primary interface; `synthesize()` is the convenience wrapper.** `synthesize_stream` is the abstract method concrete engines implement. `synthesize()` just below it concatenates the stream — prefer `synthesize_stream` directly when time-to-first-audio matters, since it lets a caller start playback on the first chunk instead of waiting for the whole utterance."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/tts/piper.py",
      "line": 51,
      "pattern": "async def synthesize_stream\\(self, text: str\\)",
      "description": "**Stage 6: local TTS, genuinely streaming.** Piper's own `synthesize()` is a **blocking sync generator**. This bridges it to async the same way `MicrophoneStream.stream()` does — a background thread pushes converted float32 chunks onto a queue, and `synthesize_stream` yields each one via `asyncio.to_thread(chunk_queue.get)` as soon as it's ready.\n\n**Data handoff:** sanitized text → a stream of float32 PCM chunks. This used to buffer the *entire* response into one list before returning anything — measured improvement from switching to real streaming: **first chunk at ~143ms vs. ~1574ms total** on a 20-sentence passage (~11x faster time-to-first-audio)."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/orchestrator/orchestrator.py",
      "line": 225,
      "pattern": "async def _speak\\(self, text: str\\)",
      "description": "**Final handoff: synthesized audio → speakers, genuinely streamed.** `_speak` calls `self._player.play_stream(self._tts.synthesize_stream(text), ...)` — chunks flow from Piper to the speakers as they're produced, not buffered into one array first. (This step used to describe a whole-utterance `synthesize()`/`play()` call as the current state with streaming as a \"known next step\" — that step has since landed; see the '2. Review Findings' tour for the measured before/after.)\n\nAlso worth knowing from here: `Orchestrator.__init__` takes an optional `on_event` callback (any caller can observe the raw backend event stream, e.g. the `--tui` conversation view) and an optional `tier_responses` flag (speaks only the first paragraph of a multi-paragraph response, with `has_more_to_reveal()`/`speak_more()` exposing the rest for a \"tell me more\" follow-up) — both off by default, zero behavior change unless a caller opts in."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/convobox/audio/playback.py",
      "line": 9,
      "pattern": "class AudioPlayer:",
      "description": "**Stage 7: playback, with barge-in.** `AudioPlayer.stop()` is what makes barge-in possible — a response can be cut off the instant the user starts speaking again, rather than waiting for playback to finish. `Orchestrator.handle_transcript`'s hard-stop path (step 12 in this tour) calls exactly this.\n\n`play()` opens a fresh `sd.OutputStream` per call rather than reusing one — a real but modest overhead (tens of ms of device-open latency per response), deliberately left as-is for now since fixing it would mean reworking a test suite that deliberately asserts today's open/close-per-call behavior. See README → Status for the full reasoning."
    },
    {
      "title": "End of tour",
      "description": "That's the full `src/convobox/` loop: **mic → VAD → STT → safeword → orchestrator → adapter → TTS → playback**, with a hard-stop escape hatch that can short-circuit at the orchestrator regardless of where the rest of the pipeline is.\n\n**Not covered by this tour, since it lives in `scripts/run_convobox.py`'s main loop rather than `src/convobox/`**: several more pure state-machine gates sit between the safeword check and the orchestrator call in the REAL running loop -- `ListeningGate` (pause/resume: \"stop listening\" hard-stops and pauses, only the wake word resumes), `BargeInMonitor` + `QueuedInterjection` (the two-axis interrupt-preset grid: what happens to the current turn vs. the user's new words), and `ContinuePromptGate` (the response-tiering silence-timeout gate: \"continue\"/\"go on\" reveals the rest of a tiered response, silence implies done). All follow the exact same pure-state-machine shape as the classes this tour walked through, unit-tested independent of real audio/clocks -- see `docs/DESIGN-barge-in.md` and `docs/DESIGN-0.3.0-interaction-and-safety.md` for the design reasoning, not re-derived here.\n\nTwo follow-up tours: **\"2. Review Findings: Security & Performance\"** for the concrete bugs a review pass found and fixed in this exact code, and **\"3. Extension Points: Modularity & Pluggability\"** for exactly where a collaborator can plug in a new backend adapter or TTS engine (and where they deliberately can't). Command Palette → CodeTour: Start Tour."
    }
  ]
}
